Map — key to value lookup.

Map is the immutable hash map. It maps keys to values, with unique keys. You construct one with the arrow notation — a key, an arrow, a value — wrapping a series of those pairs in map of parentheses.

Lookup has two forms. The unsafe form calls the map like a function, with the key in parentheses, and returns the value directly — or throws a no-such-element exception if the key is missing. The safe form calls get with the key and returns an option — some of the value if present, none if missing. Notebook six covers option in depth. There is also get-or-else, which returns the value if present and a supplied default otherwise, without involving option at all.

You modify a map by deriving a new one. Adding a pair gives a new map with that entry, removing a key gives a new map without it, and the updated method changes the value at an existing key. All of them return new maps and leave the original alone.

One thing worth understanding is the arrow notation itself. The arrow is not special syntax built into map. The arrow operator is defined on every value, and it simply returns a two-element tuple. So a key arrow a value is just the tuple of key and value, and map of parentheses is a collection of such tuples. That is exactly why iterating a map yields tuples, and why you can destructure each entry into a name and a value inside a for expression.
